            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Idris Reyes\u2019s story is one of measured ascent, a slow and steady climb from the grit of West Oakland to a corner office overlooking San Francisco\u2019s Financial District. Born to a longshoreman father and a high school administrator mother, Idris\u2019s upbringing was defined by the dual lessons of hard, physical labor and the imperative of education as a way out. He was the first in his family to finish college, crossing the Bay Bridge every day to attend San Francisco State University, where he earned a degree in Finance. His calm, analytical nature was perfectly suited for the world of numbers.\n\nHis career wasn't a rocket ship but a meticulously built skyscraper. He started as an analyst in the late 90s, diligently working his way up through the ranks. The defining moment of his professional life was the 2008 financial meltdown. While others panicked or pursued reckless gains, Idris became known for his steady hand and ethical compass, successfully navigating his firm\u2019s assets through the storm. This performance solidified his reputation and set him on the path to becoming a Managing Director.\n\nPersonally, his life has been similarly deliberate. A marriage in his late twenties ended amicably a decade later, leaving him with his greatest pride: his daughter, Anika, now a graduate student in Boston. His Hayes Valley condo, a modern space filled with jazz records and books on economic history, is his sanctuary. He eschews the hassle of a car for the 2.5-mile MUNI ride to his office, a daily ritual that gives him 20 minutes to read or simply watch the city wake up.\n\nAt 53, Idris finds himself looking beyond balance sheets. He feels a growing pull to mentor young, underrepresented professionals trying to break into finance, to offer them the guidance he never had. He dreams of a future with more travel, perhaps spending a month in Lisbon or Buenos Aires, not as a tourist, but as a temporary resident. While he still thrives on the intellectual challenge of his work, his ultimate aspiration is to build a legacy of mentorship and finally trade his portfolio management for the simpler, richer return of a life well-lived."
