            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the smell of diesel and salt air at the Port of Oakland, aged nine. His father, dwarfed by the skeletal cranes, pointed out a container ship. \"That one's from Shanghai,\" he\u2019d said, his hands calloused and stained. It wasn't just a job; it was the world arriving at their doorstep. In that moment, Idris understood the weight of physical labor. It cemented a quiet resolve in him: his own work with numbers had to honor the real, tangible effort his father put into every day.\n\n2.\nHe recalls a specific ride home from SF State during his senior year. The MUNI train emerged from the Twin Peaks tunnel, and the city sprawled below, glittering as dusk settled. He wasn't just crossing the Bay anymore; he was becoming part of this new landscape. A profound sense of arrival washed over him, not of victory, but of quiet belonging. It was the moment San Francisco stopped being a destination and started feeling like his own meticulously chosen home.\n\n3.\nOctober 2008. The office was a sea of controlled panic, phones ringing with terrified clients. He remembers looking out his window at the silent city lights, a stark contrast to the chaos inside. In that moment of intense pressure, a strange calm settled over him. It wasn't about winning; it was about protecting what people had entrusted to him. That night solidified his core belief: in a storm, the only reliable anchor is an ethical compass. It was the night he truly became a leader.\n\n4.\nHe remembers the hum of the departure hall at Logan Airport two years ago, after helping Anika move into her Boston apartment. She turned to him, no longer a child but a peer, and said, \"Thanks, Dad. I've got it from here.\" The pride that swelled in his chest was immense, followed by a quiet, hollow echo. His most important project was successfully launched. That moment wasn't an ending, but the beginning of a question: with her future secure, what would he build for himself next?\n\n5.\nLast month, on his usual MUNI ride, he saw a young man, no older than twenty, highlighting a finance textbook with fierce concentration. He had the same look of hungry determination Idris remembered in his own reflection in the train window thirty years ago. In him, he saw the entire journey: the grit, the hope, the overwhelming odds. The urge to reach out, to tell him 'you can do this,' was visceral. It was the moment his legacy shifted from portfolios to people."
